physdesc.extent: 57 letter document storage boxes, 42x32 flat box

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Records more than 10 years old are open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Information regarding the Rockefeller Archive Center's preferred elements and forms of citation can be found at http://www.rockarch.org/research/citations.php

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The material in this collection documents the work and administrative functions of the Greenacre Foundation. The contents include meeting agendas and minutes, special program files, and a set of materials on the ongoing operation of Greenacre Park.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Created in 1968 by Abby (Babs) Rockefeller Mauzé, the Greenacre Foundation's mission is to maintain and operate one or more parks in New York State for the benefit of the public. An operating foundation, Greenacre provides grants to other organizations to fulfill their mission, and has helped preserve, revitalize, and enhance open spaces in Fort Tryon, Battery Park, Bryant Park, and Union Square. Mrs. Mauzé served as the Foundation's first president.

In 1971, the Greenacre Foundation established Greenacre Park, a small vest-pocket park and waterfall on 51st Street in Manhattan. Designed by Sasaki, Dawson, DeMay Associates, Mrs. Mauzé's vision for the park was that it would provide New Yorkers "some moments of serenity in this busy world."

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is arranged into three series:
Series 1, Administrative Files Series 2, Projects Series 3, Additions to Collection

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: RAC users must abide by all applicable provisions of United States copyright law. Reproduction/duplication of archival items is routinely provided in accordance with "fair use." If the RAC does not hold copyright for an archival collection, or items within a collection, it is the user's responsibility to contact the copyright holder, or make a fair effort to do so, prior to publication.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center received the records of the Greenacre Foundation beginning in 1992, with a certificate of gift signed in 1997. Upon request from the Greenacre Foundation, the collection was formally deaccessioned and returned to the Foundation. In 2015, these materials were returned to the Archive Center, along with a set of new records.
